# Plan — Freight Factoring & Banking Operations Console

STATUS: READY. All research questions answered (pre-researcher.out); no remaining unknowns block build.

## Demo concept (locked)
Single Next.js 15 (App Router) admin/ops console backed by a real NestJS + Drizzle + Postgres service, fronted same-origin via mw-backend (Flask) reverse-proxy gateway. Richness 10 -> full functional build.

## Prototype vs full decision
FULL. No CLAUDE.md fallback trigger applies. File-cap interpretation (confirmed, CEO to bless): the 12-file cap covers touches on EXISTING repos only (michaelwegter.com, mw-backend) — estimate 4-6 touches (workSamples.js entry, `factoring_gateway_blueprint.py`, its `server.py` registration line, one additive `Start-Node` block in `run-server.ps1`). The new NestJS+Next.js app is fresh scaffolding under `upwork-runs/<slug>/demo-src/`, sized by the 180s build-timeout cap, not the file-count cap.

## Bridge mechanism (resolved, no longer an unknown)
- New `factoring_gateway_blueprint.py` in mw-backend: stdlib `urllib.request` reverse proxy (zero new deps), registered in `server.py` (1 line), forwards `/api/factoring/*` -> `http://localhost:<NEST_PORT>/*`, passes method/body/headers (Authorization, cookies) through verbatim, relays response verbatim.
- One additive `Start-Node` block in `run-server.ps1`, mirroring the existing `Start-Flask`/`Start-Tunnel` `ProcessStartInfo` pattern exactly, added to the monitor loop's restart-on-exit check. Surgical, additive, matches an existing pattern used twice already.
- Use corepack (`corepack enable && corepack prepare pnpm@latest --activate`) to get pnpm on the Surface — do not assume pnpm preinstalled.
- Risk flagged for Michael (human-in-loop, not blocking the plan): confirm Node is actually installed on the physical Surface before/at deploy. Fallback if absent: host the Nest app on a small external always-on Node host, Flask proxies to its public URL instead of localhost — no other architecture change needed.

## Database (resolved)
- Build-time real-DB integration tests: local/Docker Postgres (both confirmed installed on dev machine) — `docker run postgres:16-alpine`, schema push, factoring + ledger tests only. Satisfies "no mocks on money paths" gate within the 180s cap.
- Live deployed runtime DB: managed free-tier Postgres (Neon or Supabase) via `DATABASE_URL` env var. Decouples the live app from needing Postgres installed on the Windows Surface; also de-risks the bridge fallback (works whether Nest runs on the Surface or an external host).

## Reference structure to clone (resolved, no `nest new`/interactive scaffolds)
```
apps/api/        - NestJS, Express adapter (lighter than Fastify for 3 modules)
  src/auth/ src/factoring/ src/ledger/ src/main.ts src/app.module.ts
apps/web/        - Next.js 15 App Router admin console
packages/db/     - drizzle schema.ts (hand-written), drizzle.config.ts, client.ts
turbo.json, pnpm-workspace.yaml, package.json (root)
```
Write `schema.ts` by hand (4 tables below), run `drizzle-kit generate` once non-interactively, apply via a small `migrate.ts` at boot/test-setup. Nest CLI used only for `nest build`.

## Hero + supporting features (locked, 1+2 cap)
- **Hero:** Freight Invoice Factoring Flow — carrier submits invoice -> integer-cents advance/fee/reserve calc -> underwriter approves -> disbursement -> FIDC ledger entry (advance leg). Money-correctness showcase.
- **Supporting 1:** Banking Ledger & Account Balances — double-entry ledger, real-time balances, Drizzle relations. If time allows, add the collection/reserve-release ledger event as a second posting (3-step lifecycle: advance -> collection -> reserve release); otherwise document it in UI copy as a planned next step rather than building it.
- **Supporting 2:** RBAC & Permissions — admin/underwriter/carrier/driver roles, NestJS Guards, seeded logins, role-gated nav/actions, graceful permission-denied states.

## Scope fence
- NestJS modules: `auth`, `factoring` (invoices + approval + disbursement), `ledger` (accounts + entries). 3 max.
- Drizzle schema: `users`, `accounts`, `invoices`, `ledger_entries`. 4 tables max.
- Next.js routes: `/login`, `/dashboard`, `/invoices/new`, `/underwriter/queue`, `/ledger`, `/accounts/:id`. 6 max.
- Money: integer minor units end to end (DB columns, Zod-validated API payloads); formatted to decimal only at render time. Currency as discriminated union `{ currency: 'USD'|'BRL', minorUnits: number }` — nods to PIX/BRL nice-to-have without building real PIX.
- Seeded demo accounts: admin, underwriter, carrier — record exact credentials in demo-builder's output for deploy-test login.
- Real Postgres integration tests scoped to factoring calc + ledger posting only (money paths), not full CRUD.

## Design direction (finalized, no TBDs)
Brazilian fintech / neobank-meets-freight-ops. Deep ink-navy base (~`#0B1220`). Accent: **emerald/teal** (decided over violet — avoids reading as a Nubank-purple knockoff; signals cash-flow/liquidity, fits BaaS category convention of one confident accent on dark ink). Inter or Geist for UI text. IBM Plex Mono for all money figures, tabular numerals. Data-dense tables, status badges, role-aware nav. Explicitly NOT michaelwegter.com's palette/fonts/theme.

## Domain authenticity (for copy + ledger entries)
- Advance rate 80-95% of invoice face value; factoring fee 1-4%, tiered by payer days-to-pay; reserve = invoice amount minus advance, released to carrier (minus fee) on collection or absorbed as loss if uncollectible.
- Double-entry on advance: Debit Factoring Receivable, Credit Cash/Bank. (Collection leg, if built: Debit Cash/Bank, Credit Factoring Receivable + recognize Fee Revenue + release Reserve.)

